4\. New Findings from RMC Analysis

Items discovered during RMC analysis not previously documented in
project materials.

4.1 Default Benefit for Married Members Who Fail to Elect

**RMC:** §18-410(a)(1) \| Priority: HIGH \| Affects workspace logic

If a married member and spouse fail to consent to a distribution form,
the default is a 50% Joint and Survivor annuity (actuarial equivalent of
single life annuity). The workspace must enforce this: no married member
proceeds to payment without either a J&S election or signed spousal
consent form.

**Action:** Add default-to-50%-J&S rule. Workspace must flag married
members without completed spousal consent.

4.2 Automatic Deferred Member Classification

**RMC:** §18-402(10) and §18-408 preamble \| Priority: HIGH \| Affects
process orchestration

A deferred member is one who does not submit the required retirement
application within 30 days of separation. This is automatic --- no
appeal or extension process in the statute. Any subsequent retirement is
a deferred retirement with benefits paid prospectively only.

**Action:** Process orchestrator must track 30-day window. After 30
days, member status changes to deferred automatically.

4.3 Historical Vesting: 10 Years Pre-1987

**RMC:** §18-402(31) \| Priority: LOW \| Seed data only

Members appointed before January 1, 1987 required 10 years to vest.
Post-1987 but pre-July 2011: 5 years or age 65 (whichever earlier).
Post-July 2011: 5 years regardless of age. Seed data generator should
use era-appropriate thresholds.

4.4 Rule of 75/85 Must Be Attained While Active

**RMC:** §18-402(20) \| Priority: HIGH \| Affects eligibility engine

The Rule must be attained while employed as an active member, prior to
termination. If a member terminates after earning the required credited
service but before reaching minimum age (55/60), they may not apply
until reaching that minimum age. The eligibility engine must check both
sum threshold AND minimum age.

**Action:** Eligibility engine shows \'Rule met --- benefits available
at age XX\' for deferred members who met sum while active but haven't
reached minimum age.

4.5 Death Benefit Schedules --- Explicit Dollar Amounts

**RMC:** §18-411(d)(1-2) \| Priority: MEDIUM \| Confirms calculation
approach

The RMC provides explicit dollar-amount schedules rather than formulas,
confirming integer-age reduction:

  ----------- ----------------------------- -----------------------------
  **Age**     **Pre-July 2011 (T1&T2)**     **On/After July 2011 (T3)**

  65+         \$5,000                       \$5,000

  64          \$4,750                       \$4,500

  63          \$4,500                       \$4,000

  62          \$4,250                       \$3,500

  61          \$4,000                       \$3,000

  60          \$3,750                       \$2,500

  59          \$3,500                       ---

  58          \$3,250                       ---

  57          \$3,000                       ---

  56          \$2,750                       ---

  55          \$2,500                       ---
  ----------- ----------------------------- -----------------------------

Confirms \$250/year for Tiers 1&2, \$500/year for Tier 3. Re-employed
members per §18-408(j) are not entitled to a subsequent death benefit
--- original amount applies.

4.6 Re-Employment Creates Bridged Benefits

**RMC:** §18-408(j)(1) \| Priority: MEDIUM \| Future data model

When a retired member returns to work, benefits are suspended. Upon
subsequent retirement, the member receives a 'bridged benefit' ---
separately calculated retirement benefits combined into one payment.
Re-employed members after July 1, 2011 earn new service under Tier 3
formula regardless of original tier. Original benefit amount never
changes. Member is considered vested as of re-employment date.

4.7 DRO Alternate Payees Excluded from Health Benefits

**RMC:** §18-418(b)(8) \| Priority: HIGH \| Resolves Q-DRO-01

The RMC explicitly states: no health benefits shall be paid to or made
available for the former spouse. This definitively answers Q-DRO-01: the
DRO alternate payee is NOT eligible for IPR or any health benefits. Case
4 should not include IPR for Patricia.

4.8 Layoff-Reinstated Employees Retain Leave Payout Eligibility

**RMC:** §18-402(15) \| Priority: LOW \| Edge case

Employees hired on or before December 31, 2009 who are later laid off
and then reinstated (as defined in career service rules) continue to
have the unused leave payout included in their gross pay calculation.
This is an important exception to the general post-2009 exclusion rule.

5\. Social Security Make-Up Benefit

> *POC Status: OUT OF SCOPE for initial build. Fully documented here for
> future phase implementation.*

5.1 Statutory Authority

**RMC Section:** §18-409(i)

**Applicability:** Members employed BEFORE July 1, 2011 (Tiers 1 & 2
only) who retire on or after January 1, 1996

**Excluded:** Tier 3 members (explicitly inapplicable per statute).
Disability retirees under §18-409(c) or (d).

5.2 Benefit Commencement

The SS Make-Up benefit is paid monthly beginning at the LATER of:

**(a)** The member's retirement date, or

**(b)** The first business day of the calendar month immediately
following the member's 62nd birthday

5.3 Calculation Formula

**SS Make-Up = Estimated Primary SS Benefit × (Years of SS-Contributing
Service / 35) × Applicable Percentage**

Where:

**Estimated Primary SS Benefit** (§18-409(i))

> The estimated monthly amount payable under Title II of the Social
> Security Act at the later of age 62 or actual retirement date if after
> 62. For prior years where information is unavailable, the plan may
> assume wages increased at the national average wage index rate per SS
> Act §209(k)(1). If a member is already receiving SS benefits when they
> become eligible for the make-up, the initial entitlement amount of
> that SS benefit is used (even if based on another person's record,
> e.g. spousal benefit).

**Years of SS-Contributing Service** (§18-409(i))

> Years of credited service during which the member contributed toward
> Social Security income replacement benefits. Maximum of 35 years.

**Applicable Percentage** (§18-409(i))

> Determined by year of birth per the statutory table below.

**Birth Year Percentage Table (from RMC §18-409(i))**

  ----------------------------------- -----------------------------------
  **Year of Birth**                   **Applicable %**

  Before 1938                         0.00%

  1938                                1.25%

  1939                                2.50%

  1940                                3.75%

  1941                                5.00%

  1942                                6.25%

  1943--1954                          7.50%

  1955                                8.75%

  1956                                10.00%

  1957                                11.25%

  1958                                12.50%

  1959                                13.75%

  1960 and after                      15.00%
  ----------------------------------- -----------------------------------

5.4 Implementation Notes

**Key challenges for future implementation:** (1) Requires access to SS
benefit estimates or actual SS benefit amounts; (2) Need to determine
which years of service included SS contributions (some Denver employees
may have been exempt from SS in certain periods); (3) The 'estimated
primary SS benefit' calculation uses national average wage index
assumptions for missing data years; (4) If member is already receiving
SS on a different basis (spousal, widower), that amount is still used as
the input.

