7.2 DROP Distribution Options

Both programs offer similar distribution methods (per §18-425 and
§18-430.3):

  -------- ---------------- --------------------------------------------------
  **\#**   **Option**       **Description**

  1        **Deferral**     Delay any payments (must start by April 1 after
                            age 70½)

  2        **Lump Sum**     Full balance in single payment

  3        **Fixed Amount** Monthly payments of designated amount until
                            depleted

  4        **Fixed Period** Monthly payments over designated years
                            (recalculated annually)

  5        **Min Required   Based on life expectancy
           Distribution**   

  6        **Combo**        Initial lump sum + monthly payments

  7        **Rollover**     All or portion to IRA or eligible retirement plan
                            per §18-416

  8        **Other (DROP II Any other IRS-consistent method approved by the
           only)**          plan
  -------- ---------------- --------------------------------------------------

7.3 Key DROP Details for Data Model

**Member during DROP:** Remains an active employee for all purposes
except retirement plan membership. Earns no additional service credits
or benefits. Employer continues to contribute to the trust based on
participant's salary.

**Beneficiary rules:** Participant designates beneficiary for DROP
account. May designate multiple beneficiaries or a trust, but ONLY for
lump-sum distribution. If multiple beneficiaries designated, interest
ceases accruing upon member's death.

**Leave payout:** Calculated at BOTH DROP entry and exit. Entry: per
§18-124 and 18-135. Exit: paid for hours accrued during the DROP period.

**Re-hire after DROP:** If rehired within 60 days and no distribution
received, member may continue in DROP for remaining period OR resume
regular membership. If they resume membership, bridged benefit rules
apply per §18-408(j).

7.4 Implementation Considerations

**While both DROP programs are closed to new entrants, NoUI must
support:** (1) Displaying DROP account balances for members in the
distribution phase; (2) Processing DROP distribution elections; (3)
Correctly calculating bridged benefits for members who continued
employment after DROP; (4) Handling DRO interactions with DROP accounts
(lump-sum only per §18-418(b)(11)); (5) Interest crediting on
undistributed balances. These are all data model and process
considerations for a future phase when CSR workspaces need to support
DROP-related inquiries.

